Introduction

Introduce the dataset In this project, we will explore a dataset from Prosper, a peer-to-peer lending platform. The dataset contains loan data for approximately 113,000 loans made through Prosper from 2005 to 2014. Each row represents a loan, and the columns contain information about the borrower, the loan status, and other relevant financial information.

The goal of this exploratory data analysis is to better understand borrower behavior and loan characteristics, identify patterns, and uncover factors that may influence loan outcomes (such as default or repayment).headers and text that organize your thoughts, findings, and what you plan on investigating next.

What is the structure of your dataset?

The dataset contains 81 columns and over 100,000 records. These columns include borrower APR, credit grade, loan status, employment status, income range, and more.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main features of interest are:

BorrowerAPR: the annual percentage rate charged to the borrower.

LoanStatus: the current status of the loan (e.g., Completed, Chargedoff, Current).

CreditGrade / ProsperRating (Alpha): reflects borrower risk.

IncomeRange, EmploymentStatus, and Term.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Term: the length of the loan.

EmploymentStatus: employment of the borrower.

IncomeRange: income category.

ProsperRating (Alpha) or CreditGrade: risk rating.

LoanOriginalAmount: the amount of money borrowed.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

Borrower APR vs Prosper Rating: Borrower APR decreases significantly as Prosper Rating improves from HR (high risk) to AA (low risk). This suggests that borrowers with higher creditworthiness are offered lower interest rates.

Borrower Rate vs Debt-to-Income Ratio: There is a slight positive correlation as the Debt-to-Income Ratio increases, the Borrower Rate tends to increase. This reflects that borrowers with higher debt loads are considered riskier and charged higher rates.

Loan Status vs Income Range: Higher income borrowers tend to have more Current or Completed loans, while lower income groups have a higher presence of Chargedoff or Defaulted loans. This suggests a link between income and ability to repay.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Employment Status and APR: Employed borrowers tend to receive lower APRs compared to unemployed or part-time workers, indicating that job stability influences lending rates.

Loan Term and Loan Amount: Longer loan terms (e.g., 60 months) are generally associated with higher loan amounts, suggesting that larger loans require longer periods for repayment.

Income Range and Loan Status: As observed in the clustered bar chart, borrowers in higher income brackets are more likely to complete or remain current on their loans.

How does Borrower APR vary by Loan Status across different Income Ranges?

In[50]:
income_order = ["$0", "$1-24,999", "$25,000-49,999", "$50,000-74,999", "$75,000-99,999", "$100,000+"]
df1['IncomeRange'] = pd.Categorical(df1['IncomeRange'], categories=income_order, ordered=True)
g = sns.FacetGrid(data=df1, col='IncomeRange', col_wrap=3, height=4)
g.map_dataframe(sns.boxplot, x='LoanStatus', y='BorrowerAPR')
g.set_xticklabels(rotation=45)
g.fig.subplots_adjust(top=0.9)
g.fig.suptitle('APR by Loan Status across Income Ranges')
plt.show()
In[51]:

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?

The Facet Plot revealed that the BorrowerAPR is influenced by a combination of LoanStatus and IncomeRange. Specifically, Chargedoff and Defaulted loans in lower income brackets tend to have higher APRs, which strengthens the relationship between income and repayment performance.

The Pairplot showed a strong positive correlation between BorrowerAPR and BorrowerRate, reinforcing the idea that both represent borrowing costs and reflect similar risk factors.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

Yes, one surprising interaction was the extent to which IncomeRange amplified the impact of LoanStatus on APR. For example, the same loan status (e.g., Chargedoff) led to much higher APRs in lower income groups compared to higher income groups.

Another interesting point from the pairplot is that DebtToIncomeRatio, while weakly correlated on its own, interacts with Loan Amount to help differentiate high-risk borrowers who take large loans despite high debt burdens.

Conclusions

The majority of loans are either Completed or Current.

Borrower APR is strongly related to Prosper Rating higher-rated borrowers receive lower APRs.

Borrowers with higher income ranges tend to complete their loans more often.

A relationship exists between Loan Amount, APR, and Prosper Rating lower-rated borrowers pay higher interest regardless of loan size.
